Languages today, as a course of choice, are considered as important as courses related to science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK’s Employment and Skills Committee revealed that, in terms of the reasons why employers were having difficulty filling vacancies, a 17 percent share of the class was related to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, the need to acquire language skills is becoming increasingly imperative, so that young people are prepared for their future professional careers.
As more future employment opportunities require language proficiency, these skills are essential in a globalized world. -
Regardless of the career you will choose, if you have learned a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future, because of this skill that you will be able to use throughout your life.
If someone is able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, then automatically this multilingual person will have an advantage over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of respondents were not able to speak a foreign language well enough to make a conversation, while French was the only language that spoke two-digit (15 percent of respondents).
For this reason, investing in language teaching today is important for today's children.
The knowledge of many languages, especially the languages of the developing economies, will give children better opportunities to find meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some schools will focus on the most classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered more important to the UK with a 2020 horizon, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
For whatever your child is interested in, there will always be some languages to choose from in independent schools, which have specialized teaching staff in this area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds for them.
One cannot deny today that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be extremely important for the future of the country, so this reality should be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should be regarded as truly "international communication skills" (international communication skills).
Independent schools will continue to provide this choice, multiculturalism and excellence for Scotland’s youth.
They have to do it.
