The new twist of this technology legend is Inrupt, a company based on Berners Lee’s open Solids platform.
The Solid platform allows users to choose where their data will be stored, as well as who will be able to access it and what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt is “global sovereignty.”
“We have to do it now,” he said of the startup.
“It’s a historic moment.”
The application uses the technology of the Solid platform allowing users to create their own "personal electronic data storage space" or a POD.
It may contain contact lists, pending task lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify being all available in one browser and all at the same time.
The unique feature of the personal electronic data storage space is that it allows the user to decide who has access to what kind of information.
The company calls this capability “personal empowerment through data.”
The idea of Inrupt, according to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, is the company to offer resources, processes and appropriate skills so that the Solid platform is available to everyone.
The company consists of Berners Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some contracted developers who worked on the project, and a community of volunteer code developers.
As of this week, tech developers around the world can create their own decentralized apps using the tools available on Inrupt’s website.
Berners Lee said he and his team are not talking to “Facebook and Google about whether they are allowed to make radical changes, overturning business models overnight.
"We're not asking them for permission."
In a Medium post released on Saturday, Berners Lee wrote that “Inrupt’s mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that will protect the integrity and quality of the new web created on the Solid platform.”
In 1994, Berners Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT).
In recent months, Berners Lee has been a strong voice in the debate over the neutrality of the Internet.
Even with Inrupt, Berners Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m extremely optimistic about the next era of the Internet,” Berners Lee added.
