According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Van led his battalion to the St. Kendall Canal in the midst of very dense fog and while receiving heavy fire from combat weapons and machine guns.
Later, he hurried to the front line and with "excellent courage" led the line forward, before hitting himself with a three-gun combat weapon from the squad.
Lieutenant Colonel Van was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, almost a month before the end of the war.
Michael Van, 72, said his grandfather's heroic actions were "something I know I could never reach, it's something that makes you feel unlimited respect."
He and his brother, Dr. James Van, also deposited a wreath after the parade, which was led by the young Brentwood Philharmonic Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Van said he "felt great honor to have attended the parade" and added that "the bravery of a true hero is demonstrated by the support he has from many people."
