The National Trust is hiding the secret life of bats
A new research conducted at a farm in the Highlands of Scotland seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape when hunting for their food.
The findings will shed new light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and will contribute to the design of future actions to protect the environment.
The study by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will explore the habits of the common nanobite and the small bat, as well as the brown bat and dompton’s myotis in Inverewe Gardens, in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the property to monitor the activities of bats throughout the season.
NTS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld scanners.
An analysis of the sound of all recordings by specialists will verify the frequency of calls of bats, as well as what species have this behavior.
A map of the habitat and a report will then be created to form a detailed picture of their behavior on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, natural environment protection consultant for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help identify the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of meadows and the best way to conserve forests for bats and other related species.
The populations of bats in Scotland and across the UK have declined significantly since the last century.
They are threatened by construction work and development projects that affect the places where they gnaw and destroy their habitats.
Wind turbines and lighting are also hazardous, as are adhesive tapes for flies and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks from domestic cats.
The bats are not actually blind.
However, because they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes to catch their prey.
They use an advanced sound sensing technique to detect insects and obstacles in the course of their flight.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, considers bats very important.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct research, inspect the places where bats roam, and sometimes rescue them.
The organization has also created Scotland’s first and only exclusively for bats shelter at Threave Estate, Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of Scotland’s ten bat species live.
The farm manager, David Thompson, states that the farm is the ideal land for bats.
"Here at Threave we have an excellent area for bats," he said.
“We have the old buildings, a lot of big trees and an ideal habitat.
There’s still a lot we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need to grow their populations.”
It stresses that it is important to first check for the presence of bats before any maintenance work in homes, as the destruction of a single nest with small ones could kill up to 400 females and small ones, possibly eliminating the entire local population.
Fleas are protected species and it is forbidden to kill them, harass them or disturb their tranquility, or destroy their nests.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a member of the Bat Conservation Trust in Scotland, encouraged the public to offer her help.
He said: "There's still a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we just don't know the evolution of their populations."
