Syria is “ready” for the return of the refugees, according to the Foreign Minister
Syria says it is ready to voluntarily return refugees and is calling for help to rebuild the country, which has been devastated by the seven-year war.
Speaking at the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Muhammad said conditions in the country are improving.
"Today the situation in the country is more stable and safe thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rebuild the areas destroyed by the terrorists to restore normality.
All conditions are now met for the voluntary return of refugees to the country who were forced to flee because of terrorism and the unilateral economic measures that hampered their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the war broke out in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country are in need of humanitarian aid.
Al-Muhammad said aid to rebuild the destroyed country was welcomed by the Syrian government.
However, he stressed that he would not accept conditional aid or assistance from countries that supported the uprising.
